The Great Oasis (Deepwell Confluence) is the primary water source in the eastern desert.
Three underground springs rise through fractured limestone into a shallow basin.
It is the only reliable year-round water source within six days' travel. All caravan routes converge here.

The Keepers of Measure built the Cistern Ring: four underground chambers governing daily distribution, drought emergency, caravan provisioning, and irrigation.
The four sluice masters formed the Water Court, the earliest governing body in the desert.
The Measuring House was aligned to true cardinal; roof apertures cast sunlight on calibration marks at precise times.
The Waystone Circle (twelve limestone slabs) encoded directional glyphs and legal formulae in Measure Script.

The Salt Ledger Kingdoms later built a Toll Pavilion atop the ruined Measuring House.
The High Water Court became supreme arbiter for water-right disputes across the road network.
Garden terraces at the margins were tended by the hereditary Reed Tenders caste.

The springs have diminished since the Iseth Reach dried and the Ninth Meridian Rite failed.
The Cistern Ring still functions. Water Court legal formulae still govern desert trade.
